at these opinions but they are exactly mine too.<BR>It just plainly sucks if you have to travel from deep inside a dungeon to a town healer just to get rid of a little poisoning. It also sucks if you have to abort some long overland journey just because one of your characters sneezes his brains out. It IS annoying and if it happens randomly players will indeed just revert to save/reload to prevent these things from happening hoping they will be luckier next time.</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tutamun</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">This stuff could improve the atmosphere of the game. If it is implemented it should be tested very carefully and if it hinders gameplay then it should be removed. Even if it took time to program and render.<P>I also didn't like to eat in Darkstone. The game was more a hack&slay like Diablo. In DSA2 I didn't find it so anoying that you had to eat and drink, got sick, etc. But this realy depends on the game type and how it is implemented.<P>Getting sick should not be random but rather caused by your bahaviour like walking in rain to long, sleeping outdoors in winter, eating something bad, etc.<P>Is there going to be Spring, Summer, Autum, Winter in the game? Will the Char get older during the game?</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Anastasia</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Will I get a special "no illness" edition of Project C ?<BR>I haven´t had a flu or any other weather related illness for more than 10 years now  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"><BR>Just broke my jaws (double) and my wrist so I want the special "bone crusher" edition  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Bobby</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">How about a user menu were we can turn off each individual feature in the game:<P>Say something like:<P>eating: yes<BR>sleeping: no<BR>diseases: no<BR>poison: yes<BR>.<BR>.<BR>.<P>default settings<P>Note: If you fiddle with the default setting game balance may (will) be affected, but thats not our problem. We'll still be happily  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"> fixing any other related problems however.</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, personally I hate poison/disease. Usually that means it stands little chance of making it into the game. Actually, in general I hate everything in a rpg where time plays a role. I really don't like being rushed because it probably means I don't have enough time to explore everything. So, fat chance of time being crucial in Project C.  It's true that it adds atmosphere, and increase immersion sometimes, but I guess there's enough other ways of creating it.<P>Lar</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Arhu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Yup, nothing to add.<BR>However, those 'instant poisons' would be fine on weapons or arrows. They would effect a larger variety of possible weapon kinds. Remember that there are probably lots of diablo players out there who want to push their characters to maximum. Under no circumstances should the game become a 'push only' game, of course. But within boundaries such poison would be ok, I would say.<P><I>Meow...</I><BR>Arhu</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dante</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The only way you can use a disease of poison is when it drives your story. But the negative effects should come VERY slowly, so that - as Lar says - you are not really on a tight time schedule.<P>It could be though that you are shunned and cannot enter a specific town because they do not allow deseased people to enter etc...<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Cybu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">How about this for poison.<P>You can poison your weapons (as said before) for example with potions, with spells or just buy them poisoned (from some really mean weaponsseller so good guys forget about it  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/badsmile.gif">).<P>They have no time-related effect but work immidiately (greater loss of hp). But you can armor yourself (or vaccinate or whatever) against poison (like I said in any way possible: magic, armory, etc etc).<P>This way there could be caverns filled with spiders (can you yet imagine it...skelettons in cocoons, spiderwebs, fog, etc etc). A regular spiderlair such to speak. <P>Since spiders are quite known to be poisonous and since you might know where you're heading (cuz the exploration of the spiderlair is part of a quest) you can prepare yourself against poison.<P>Is this immersion or what ?!<P>Just admit I'm good ... urm ... evil  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P><BR>Cybu<P>------------------<BR> <BR>"And is your heart black<BR>and full of hate"<P></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Cypher</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hey lar, nice icon!<BR>is this a direct attack against Arhu?<P>poison and diseases are a nice gamefeature,<BR>if the are shown and reversable<P>nothing is better than a trap with poisoned spikes! I got some in my dungeon!<P>------------------<BR><I>Cypher</I><P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dante</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I could live with poisons with a one-time-effect that is reversible (eg damage bonus).<P>But only if the two sides can use it: the monsters and the player. I still remember leading a RPG (non computer) where one of the players constantly (over-)used poisons against the NPCs. Then I lead a story where "my" NPCs used poison against him... I never saw a player falling out of character that hard: he was outraged and yelled: "(Game) Master, what are you doing to me? This is unfair!!"<P>Dante.<P>PS: a sleep poison can be very handy to create stories too!</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ragon der Magier</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Poison and Diseases can be very nice  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">, if they are implemented in an approriate manner:<BR>Quests where you have to fetch a vaccine to cure a NPCs disease: definitely!<BR>Diseased and poisoned PC: if the player can take appropriate measures to prepare or cure afterwards (cure disease/poison potions/skill, enough time to reach those countermeasures, including healers, mages):<BR>o.k.!<BR>If the illness of a player starts a quest (perhaps forces them to contact a certain NPC who is a healer an sends the group for some ingredients he needs, then when player (or accompanying char) healed has a job for them to do as payment (which might in the end lead to another quest/NPC or just gain of story-relevant information for player...<BR>If the poison/disease is only temporarily and goes away itself.<BR>Want an example here? Well, let's stick with the poisonous spiders in their lair:<BR>Being bit by one the player slowly get's numbed by the evil juice in his veins, means he won't fight as good as before. This might be accumulated by further bites from the hairy, leggy beasts.<BR>After (hopefully) slain the unacommodating (another hope: that this is the damn right vocabulary to express what i wanted to  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">) creatures, the player slowly creeps around the dungeon, but thanks to the mighty lords of heaven he recovers to former condition and thereby regains his natural fighting power.<BR>THE END<P>You see, Lar, there's always a good thing you can a seemingly bad thing turn into!  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"><BR>(Yes, Cybu, and especially no good thing that can't be morphed into evil, but hey, that's common knowledge!  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">)<P>BTW, look at the "Nordland-Trilogie" of DSA (a game by the infamous "ATTICs" [o.k., let's look at the watch: 16:15h and go; let's see how long it'll take the little furry, lurky  animal, hehe!  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">]!).<BR>Both features, poison and disease were incorporated quite reasonable and carefully into the gameflow.<P>Your's sincerely<BR>Ragon</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, the poison attribute is there, if only because I wanted the player to be able to poison other guys food.<P>Lar</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
